libspeex (Xiph.Org Foundation)
------------------------------

The Speex speech codec support in this crate is a derivative work
of libspeex, the BSD-licensed Xiph.Org reference implementation
(primary author Jean-Marc Valin). It includes both numeric data
tables reproduced verbatim and algorithmic source files that mirror
the control flow of libspeex C sources.

Verbatim data tables
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The following Rust modules contain numeric tables transcribed
verbatim from libspeex. Values only — no derived code — and copied
under the Xiph BSD-3-Clause licence reproduced below:

  * `src/exc_tables.rs` — innovation (fixed) codebooks from
    `libspeex/exc_5_256_table.c`, `libspeex/exc_5_64_table.c`,
    `libspeex/exc_8_128_table.c`, `libspeex/exc_10_32_table.c`, and
    `libspeex/exc_20_32_table.c`.
  * `src/gain_tables.rs` — pitch-gain (LTP) codebooks from
    `libspeex/gain_table.c` and `libspeex/gain_table_lbr.c`.
  * `src/hexc_tables.rs` — high-band (SB-CELP) innovation codebooks
    from `libspeex/hexc_table.c` and `libspeex/hexc_10_32_table.c`.
  * `src/lsp_tables_nb.rs` — narrowband LSP codebooks from
    `libspeex/lsp_tables_nb.c`.
  * `src/lsp_tables_wb.rs` — wideband LSP codebooks
    (`high_lsp_cdbk`, `high_lsp_cdbk2`) from
    `libspeex/high_lsp_tables.c`.
  * `src/qmf.rs` — the 64-tap QMF analysis/synthesis prototype
    `h0[]` from `libspeex/sb_celp.c` (float path, rescaled by
    2^-16 from the reference fixed-point coefficients).

Algorithmic ports
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The following Rust modules are derivative works that mirror the
control flow, constants, and sub-frame structure of corresponding
libspeex C sources. They are not line-by-line copies but are close
enough to the reference that libspeex's BSD-3-Clause terms apply:

  * `src/nb_decoder.rs` — mirrors `nb_decode` in
    `libspeex/nb_celp.c`. Helper kernels (`pitch_unquant_3tap`,
    `forced_pitch_unquant`, `iir_mem16`, perceptual-filter and
    comb-filter helpers) are direct float ports of the equivalents
    in `libspeex/ltp.c`, `libspeex/cb_search.c`, and
    `libspeex/filters.c`. NB constants such as `LSP_MARGIN` and
    the sub-frame gain quantiser come from `libspeex/nb_celp.c` /
    `nb_celp.h`.
  * `src/submodes.rs` — reproduces the eight `nb_submodeN`
    configuration records from `libspeex/modes.c` (lbr_pitch,
    forced_pitch_gain, have_subframe_gain, nb_subvect,
    gain_bits, comb_gain, etc.) and the wideband-layer skip table
    from `libspeex/nb_celp.c`.
  * `src/wb_decoder.rs` — mirrors `sb_decode` in
    `libspeex/sb_celp.c`, including the 16-entry
    `gc_quant_bound[]` table and the spectral-folding excitation
    path.
  * `src/wb_encoder.rs` — mirrors the high-band analysis pipeline
    from `libspeex/sb_celp.c` and the QMF decomposition from
    `libspeex/filters.c` (`qmf_decomp`, float path).
  * `src/wb_submodes.rs` — reproduces the four `wb_submodeN`
    records from `libspeex/modes_wb.c`.
  * `src/uwb_decoder.rs` — mirrors the `sb_uwb_mode` configuration
    in `libspeex/modes.c` / `libspeex/sb_celp.c`
    (`lpcSize = 8`, `subframeSize = 40`, `frameSize = 320`), reusing
    the reference `wb_submode1` record.
  * `src/lsp.rs` — float-mode port of the relevant parts of
    `libspeex/lsp.c` (closed-form LSP polynomial reconstruction)
    and `libspeex/quant_lsp.c`, plus the bandwidth-expansion helper
    from `libspeex/lpc.c`.
  * `src/qmf.rs` — `qmf_synth` mirrors the synthesis loop in
    `libspeex/filters.c`.
  * `src/header.rs` — the Speex Ogg header layout mirrors
    `SpeexHeader` in `libspeex/speex_header.c`.
  * `src/lib.rs` — the MSB-first bit reader/writer matches
    `libspeex/bits.c`.

